olving the conflicts that frustrate their fulfillment.Valerie Tiberius introduces you to a way of thinking about your goals that enables you to reflect on them effectively throughout your life. She illustrates her approach with vivid examples, many of which are drawn from her own life, ranging from the silly to the serious, from shopping to navigating prejudice. Throughout, the book emphasizes the importance of interconnectedness, reminding us of the profound influence other people have on our lives, our goals, and how we should pursue them. At the same time, the book offers strategies for coping with obstacles to realizing your goals, including gender bias and other kinds of discrimination.Whether you are changing jobs, rethinking your priorities, or reconsidering your whole life path, What Do You Want Out of Life? is an essential guide to helping you understand what really matters to you and how you can thoughtfully pursue it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLife. 0aMeaning (Philosophy). 0aValues. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aA Different World.  aA Theory of Justice.  aAddiction.  aAnnoyance.  aAphorism.  aBehavior.  aBehaviour therapy.  aBoredom.  aBuridan's ass.  aCareer.  aCompetition.  aConfirmation bias.  aConflict management.  aConsequentialism.  aControversy.  aCulprit.  aDaydream.  aDebt.  aDeliberation.  aDelusion.  aDisease.  aDisgust.  aEmotion.  aEmployment.  aEthics.  aExistential crisis.  aExistentialism.  aExplanation.  aFake news.  aFeeling.  aFinding.  aGlaucon.  aGoFundMe.  aGoal seeking.  aGraduate school.  aGrief.  aGym.  aHeadache.  aHealth.  aHoax.  aHumility.  aHumour.  aImmanuel Kant.  aImpostor syndrome.  aInferiority complex.  aInstitution.  aInternal conflict.  aIntro